05911nam a2200781Ia 9781501736612DE-B159720240426104009.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240426t20192019nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a97815017366127 a10.1515/97815017366122doi  a(DE-B1597)527399  a(OCoLC)1084632005  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 4aUC403b.M33 2020 7aHIS0271102bisacsh04a973.31132231 aMcCurdy, John Gilbert, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aQuarters :bThe Accommodation of the British Army and the Coming of the American Revolution /cJohn Gilbert McCurdy. 1aIthaca, NY : bCornell University Press, c[2019] 4c©2019  a1 online resource (328 p.) :b20 b&w halftones, 3 maps  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPreface and Acknowledgments -- tA Note on Quotations, Terminology, and Money -- tIntroduction: The Importance of Place in the Age of Atlantic Revolutions -- t1. Houses: The Rise of Domestic Privacy -- t2. Barracks: Constructing a Colonial Military Infrastructure -- t3. Empire: Drafting and Implementing the Quartering Act -- t4. Borderland: Native Americans, Soldiers, and Colonists in the Backcountry -- t5. Cities and Towns: Accommodation and Eviction of the British Army -- t6. Nation: American Armies and the March toward Independence -- tEpilogue: The Third Amendment and the Shadow of Quartering -- tNotes -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aWhen Americans declared independence in 1776, they cited King George III "for quartering large bodies of armed troops among us." In Quarters, John Gilbert McCurdy explores the social and political history behind the charge, offering an authoritative account of the housing of British soldiers in America. Providing new interpretations and analysis of the Quartering Act of 1765, McCurdy sheds light on a misunderstood aspect of the American Revolution. Quarters unearths the vivid debate in eighteenth-century America over the meaning of place. It asks why the previously uncontroversial act of accommodating soldiers in one's house became an unconstitutional act. In so doing, Quarters reveals new dimensions of the origins of Americans' right to privacy. It also traces the transformation of military geography in the lead up to independence, asking how barracks changed cities and how attempts to reorder the empire and the borderland led the colonists to imagine a new nation.Quarters emphatically refutes the idea that the Quartering Act forced British soldiers in colonial houses, demonstrates the effectiveness of the Quartering Act at generating revenue, and examines aspects of the law long ignored, such as its application in the backcountry and its role in shaping Canadian provinces.Above all, Quarters argues that the lessons of accommodating British troops outlasted the Revolutionary War, profoundly affecting American notions of place. McCurdy shows that the Quartering Act had significant ramifications, codified in the Third Amendment, for contemporary ideas of the home as a place of domestic privacy, the city as a place without troops, and a nation with a civilian-led military.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Apr 2024) 0aRequisitions, MilitaryzNorth AmericaxHistoryy18th century. 0aRequisitions, MilitaryzUnited StatesxHistoryy18th century. 0aSoldiersxBilletingzNorth AmericaxHistoryy18th century. 0aSoldiersxBilletingzUnited StatesxHistoryy18th century. 4aEarly American & Colonial History. 4aMilitary History. 4aU.S. History. 7aHISTORY / Military / United States.2bisacsh  aquartering act, British army in Colonial America, American Revolution, Third Amendment, military geography, eighteenth-century America, civil–military relations in the co